CL emission were carried out with the static injection CL analysis. As shown in Fig. 2
                        A-B, strong oxidants, such as H2O2, NaClO, KMnO4, and dissolved oxygen, can trigger efficient CL from SiQDs. A control experiment was also conducted to examine the CL responses of some reductants, such as GSH, Na2S2O3, N2H4·H2O, and AA, which failed to observe any obvious CL from SiQDs (Fig. S3). The reason was probably attributed to the rich electronic nature of SiQDs, where radiative charge recombination occurred between oxidants-injected holes and pre-existing endogenous CB electrons in SiQDs. Interestingly, the CL signal was significantly enhanced by mixing the prepared SiQDs (100 μL) with reductants (Fe2+
                        ) in similar condition (Fig. 2C). The CL intensity reached the value of 120 K rapidly, and the emission was maintained for 4 s before being entirely quenched. Additionally, the CL intensity could not be observed by mixing m-PD or DAMO (precursor of prepared SiQDs) with Fe2+. Some common metal ions, including Fe3+, Cu2+, and Ti4+, were also introduced into the SiQDs solution to investigated their CL responses. As shown in Fig. 2D, we found that no CL signal can be produced except for a weak CL intensity induced by the presence of Cu2+ and Fe3+. Moreover, the UV − Vis absorption and FL emission intensity become decreased (Fig. S4A-C). combing with the shorter FL lifetime of SiQDs after CL reaction, the result indicated that the changes of the surface structure of SiQDs after Fe2+ solution treatment.
